metadata.name: Acrylic #87
metadata.description:
A deep dive into particles is what led me to acrylic. Bright and deep colours with smooth lines while all connected in the journey to the target. 
My main inspiration was the smooth movement of a flock to a endpoint and where a particle should go if not one but multiple points present itself. Make sure you take a look at the live view to see every detail of the piece. 


Generated with code using p5.js
Images are generated at 1280 x 2048px 
(all the way up to 7680 * 12288).

To save a PNG file, please press 'S'.

[URL variables in live view]:
Change size (up to 6): /&density=6

metadata.name: Livro #53
metadata.description:
A messy book is a well-read book, a sign of knowledge acquired. It's easy to spot a book that has been loved and used frequently. The pages are bent and creased, the spine is worn, and notes are scribbled in the margins. These imperfections are not a sign of neglect or carelessness, but rather an evidence of a book that has been fully engaged with and understood.
A book that is kept in pristine condition may look nice on a shelf, but it is also a sign that it has not been read as much, or not as deeply. A well-read book is an indication of a curious and active mind, always seeking to learn and grow. So, don't be afraid to let your books get a little messy, it's a sign that you're gaining knowledge and expanding your understanding of the world around you.

Made with p5.js, p5.grain and much love <3

[S] to save as image

metadata.name: Reverie #49
metadata.description:
Reverie: a state of being pleasantly lost in one's thoughts; a daydream.

I love impressionist paintings of nature, where the visible brushstrokes give a glimpse into the artist’s process. With this collection I aimed to capture a slice of nature with distinctly digital “brushstrokes”. Looking closely, you can see many of the lines, curves and polygons that combined to form each Reverie. 

Keyboard Interactions:
[z] Change color / season. There are two seasons, winter and not-winter. Weather (wind, ice) is as unpredictable as it is in nature.
[p] Play / pause. Automatically cycle through colors and seasons.
[s] Save 1000x1000px image (instant)
[2] Save 2000x2000px image (fast)
[4] Save 4000x4000px image (slowish)


Elsif 2022, made with p5js.

metadata.name: The Universal Garden of Eden #39
metadata.description:
The triptych art series "The Universal Garden of Eden" portrays the iconic biblical story via the lens of Austrian Expressionism and Symbolism conveyed through digital art. The left and right panels depict Adam and Eve in various races, distancing from traditional ideal forms, and showing a more visceral representation. By incorporating this style, the series captures the raw humanity of Adam and Eve, depicting them as real people with flaws and imperfections. This approach sheds light on the idea that perfection is not a necessary component of humanity and that all people, regardless of their appearance, are deserving of love and acceptance. The central panel shows the Garden of Eden in all its beauty, showcasing the timeless appeal of the natural world. The triptych style borrows from the medieval style of painting, creating a series that is inclusive and depicts a world for everyone, regardless of race or physical attributes. This reimagining of the Garden of Eden serves as a commentary on the universality of human experiences and the beauty of diversity.

The concept of Adam and Eve is pervasive across several religions and cultures, making it a universal story that resonates with people from all walks of life. The "Universal Garden of Eden" art series is not intended to offend any particular group or religion, but instead aims to cast the idea of humanity living together in unity as the perfect world. By portraying Adam and Eve in various races and physical attributes, the series emphasizes the importance of inclusiveness and the beauty of diversity. The depiction of the Garden of Eden as a place of peace and harmony further reinforces the idea of a world where people from all backgrounds can coexist in unity. The series invites viewers to contemplate the idea of a harmonious world where everyone is welcome and valued. 

The words accompanying images of Adam and Eve are from various languages worldwide.

metadata.name: Gentrax EP #170
metadata.description:
Gentrax EP is a generative audiovisual artwork. Each iteration produces a generative house/garage track ~3 minutes in length while drawing out accompanying artwork. Live piece is aspect ratio agnostic and scales to any window size, but an aspect of 1:1.414 is preferred and can be set with an URL parameter.

Audio controls:
1-7: Channel mutes/unmutes
a: Filter up 
z: Filter down
c: Flanger on/off
v: Reverb (cycle thru three settings)
q: Switch bassline octave&seq (cycle thru three settings)
b: Portamento on/off

Visual controls: 
p: Fast forward to final artwork
o: Save canvas

Url parameters: 
&w=800 : Set width of canvas. If aspect ratio is not defined, artwork will be in preferred aspect ratio (1.41414)
&a=1.5 : Set aspect ratio. number <1 = Wide canvas
&wl=1 : Locks canvas aspect ratio to preferred 


made with p5.js & tone.js
Using tonejs synthesis for bass plus oneshot samples from various drum machines & Alpha Juno 2
<3

CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Adjacent #139
metadata.description:
Adjacent is the third in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art. This piece focuses on the study of Diagonal White, a series he developed between 1970 and 1975.

In 1976, Ruth Leavitt published a collection of papers titled "Artist & Computer", which highlighted the 35 prominent generative artists and asked them to discuss their work. They were posed questions like, "Do you feel art work created with a computer has now or will have an impact on art as a whole in the future?". Edward Zajec was a subject of one of those papers and in it detailed the approach to Diagonal White. 

The original program was run on a CDC 6200 computer at The Univeresiry of Trieste. The programming was done in collaboration with Dr. Matjaz Hmeljak, his long-time technical partner. Inspired by his collaborative relationship, Adjacent the output of a partnership between Christine Hall and Chris Maddern.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall and @chrismaddern

metadata.name: (recombination/perspectives)-I: Horizons #94
metadata.description:
🌊 🌞 🌈 🌅


    ( r e c o m b i n a t i o n  /  p e r s p e c t i v e s ) 


                     I :   H o r i z o n s


                            ✨ 🧬 🧡 ⏲







-----
* What/How *

2 560 000 particles are subjected to a succession of 64 energy bursts which scatters the points through space. 
The algorithm then stores 3 configurations of points, forming an entangled coherent system.
After few seconds multiple observation modalities are then selected sequentially to allow for dynamic and contemplative visualization.

-----
* Mint preview *

Minter will get a 2160x2160 PNG bitmap and an infinite randomly deterministic animation.

-----
* Technics *

This experience is designed to be executed on a recent GPU (>2016) and displayed on 16/9 screens from FHD to 8K+ (1920x1080 → 7680x4320) at 60FPS for infinite duration.

- JavaScript / ThreeJS / WebGL / GLSL
- Unique generative, random and determinist animation (animation is seeded by the fxhash mint hash)
- Infinite animation
- Animation sequences duration between 6 and 60 seconds.

-----
* Controls *

Keyboard "Space" : take a PNG capture of the current view frame (same ratio as window, max 1920x1080)

Keyboard "X" : skip current animation sequence / next sequence

-----
* URL modifiers *

"&fastdemo=on"
Forces animation sequences to last 10 seconds instead of random durations.

"&slow=on"
Forces animation sequences to last 1 minute instead of random durations.

"&static=on"
Disables animation automatic start. Press "X" to start animations.


-----
@HAL09999 – January 25th, 2023
